# Mule Salesforce Connector

The Mule Salesforce connector (`mule-salesforce-connector`) supports SOAP, REST, Bulk API, Streaming API, and Composite API against any Salesforce org (Sandbox or Production).

## 0. XML Namespace Prefix — MANDATORY

The Salesforce connector's XML namespace is `http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/salesforce`. The agent MUST alias this namespace as **`salesforce:`** in every Mule XML file — never `sfdc:`.

```xml
<!-- RIGHT — every project file uses the same prefix -->
xmlns:salesforce="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/salesforce"

<salesforce:sfdc-config name="Salesforce_Dev_config">
  <salesforce:basic-connection .../>
</salesforce:sfdc-config>

<salesforce:create config-ref="Salesforce_Dev_config" type="Account">
  <salesforce:records>#[payload]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:create>
```

```xml
<!-- WRONG — older/Mule-3-era prefix; trips ACB language-server "unknown / disabled"
     warnings in Cursor and creates cross-file lint errors when one file uses
     'sfdc:' while another uses 'salesforce:' -->
xmlns:sfdc="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/salesforce"
<sfdc:sfdc-config ...>
<sfdc:create ...>
```

### Why this matters

- **The XML prefix is just a local alias** for the namespace URI — at runtime, Mule resolves by URI + element local-name, so `sfdc:create` and `salesforce:create` are functionally identical. **But** ACB / Cursor's XML language server does **prefix-string matching** on `config-ref` validation. When one file declares `<sfdc:sfdc-config name="X">` and another references it via `<salesforce:create config-ref="X">`, the linter throws `Configuration type reference is not compatible (connection config)` even though deploy + runtime are fine. Keeping ALL files on the same prefix is the only way to keep the lint clean.
- **`salesforce:` is the canonical Mule 4 prefix.** Modern MuleSoft documentation, ACB code-completion, and the connector's own examples use it. `sfdc:` is a legacy carry-over from Mule 3 (`mule-module-sfdc`). Cursor's XML language server preferentially recognizes the `salesforce:` alias.
- **Element local-names stay identical** when the prefix changes: `<salesforce:sfdc-config>` (yes, the local-name `sfdc-config` is from the XSD — that doesn't change), `<salesforce:salesforce-query>`, `<salesforce:basic-connection>`, etc. Only the prefix before the colon is renamed.

### What is NOT renamed

These are property names (matching `.env` and JVM `-M-D` flags), NOT XML prefixes — leave them as-is:
- `${sfdc.username}`, `${sfdc.password}`, `${sfdc.token}`, `${sfdc.url}` — placeholders in `global-configs.xml`
- `sfdc.username` / `sfdc.password` / `sfdc.token` keys in `.env`, `.env.example`, `scripts/run-mule.ps1` `-M-D…` lines
- `SFDC_USERNAME` / `SFDC_PASSWORD` etc. — environment variable names

The rule of thumb: **`sfdc` followed by `:` (XML prefix delimiter) is forbidden. `sfdc` followed by `.` (property name dot) or `_` (env var underscore) is fine.**

### Migrating an existing project

If an existing project still uses `sfdc:` prefix anywhere, migrate ALL files in one pass — never partially. Do this in three files at minimum:

1. `src/main/mule/global-configs.xml` — change `xmlns:sfdc="…"` → `xmlns:salesforce="…"`, then every `sfdc:` element rename (`sfdc:sfdc-config` → `salesforce:sfdc-config`, `sfdc:basic-connection` → `salesforce:basic-connection`, etc.).
2. Every `<feature>-api.xml` flow file that uses the connector — same two-step rename.
3. Every MUnit test file under `src/test/munit/` — same two-step rename.

After migration:
- Run `ReadLints` on the changed files; the cross-prefix `Configuration type reference is not compatible` errors should be gone.
- Add a row to `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` § 10 Decisions Log with the date and "migrated Salesforce XML prefix from sfdc: to salesforce: across all flow + config + test files".
- Smoke-test all endpoints (`scripts/smoke-test.ps1`) — no behavior change is expected, but the Self-Test Gate rule still applies.

## 1. Add Dependency

In `pom.xml`:

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>com.mulesoft.connectors</groupId>
  <artifactId>mule-salesforce-connector</artifactId>
  <version>11.1.0</version>
  <classifier>mule-plugin</classifier>
</dependency>
```

## 2. Global Config (in `global-configs.xml`)

Salesforce supports several auth flows. Pick ONE per org:

### Username + Password + Security Token (simplest, dev/test)
```xml
<salesforce:sfdc-config name="Salesforce_Org_config" doc:name="Salesforce Org">
  <salesforce:basic-connection
      username="${sfdc.username}"
      password="${sfdc.password}"
      securityToken="${sfdc.token}"
      url="${sfdc.url}"/>
</salesforce:sfdc-config>
```

### CRITICAL: pick the right login endpoint per org type

The agent MUST ask the user "what type of Salesforce org is this?" during init and pick the right endpoint. Wrong endpoint always returns `INVALID_LOGIN: Invalid username, password, security token` — looks like a credential issue but isn't.

| Org type | SOAP login endpoint | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| **Production** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | The "real" org |
| **Developer Edition** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Free standalone dev org from developer.salesforce.com — uses the **production** endpoint, NOT the sandbox endpoint |
| **Sandbox** (Dev/UAT/Full) | `https://test.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Forked off a Production org. Username usually has a `.sandboxname` suffix (e.g. `you@company.com.dev1`). |
| **Trailhead Playground** | `https://login.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Same as Developer Edition |
| **My Domain enabled** (any) | `https://<mydomain>.my.salesforce.com/services/Soap/u/59.0` | Org-specific URL; required if Production has My Domain login enforcement |

Never hardcode the URL in `global-configs.xml` — put it in `config.yaml` as `sfdc.url` so it can change per environment without touching XML.

### OAuth JWT Bearer (recommended for prod / server-to-server)
```xml
<salesforce:sfdc-config name="Salesforce_Prod_config" doc:name="Salesforce Prod">
  <salesforce:oauth-jwt-connection
      consumerKey="${sfdc.consumerKey}"
      keyStore="keystores/sfdc.jks"
      storePassword="${sfdc.storePassword}"
      principal="${sfdc.principal}"
      audienceUrl="https://login.salesforce.com"/>
</salesforce:sfdc-config>
```

## 3. `config.yaml` Properties

```yaml
salesforce:
  username: "integration@acme.com.sandbox"
  # password and token live in env vars or secure-properties — NEVER here
```

For secrets, NEVER inline credentials in YAML/XML and NEVER use `${env.X}` in property files — Mule 4 does not auto-resolve `${env.X}` to OS environment variables. Either:

- Inject as JVM system properties at launch (e.g. `mule.bat console -M-Dsfdc.password=...`) and reference `${sfdc.password}` from `global-configs.xml`, OR
- Use an encrypted `secure-properties.yaml` (CloudHub / on-prem secure properties module).

See `mule-init-context.mdc` "CRITICAL Mule Property Resolution Gotcha" for full details.

## 4. Operations

### Insert (Create) — single record
```xml
<salesforce:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Create Account">
  <salesforce:records>#[[{
    Name: payload.name,
    Industry: payload.industry default "Other",
    BillingCity: payload.city
  }]]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:create>
```
**Result shape**: see §5 — the connector returns `{ successful, items: [{ successful, id, payload: { success, id, errors }, ... }] }`. Read results from `payload.items[0]`, NOT `payload[0]`. The §7 pattern shows the correct success/error extraction.

### Insert — multiple records
```xml
<salesforce:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Contact" doc:name="Create Contacts">
  <salesforce:records>#[payload map { FirstName: $.firstName, LastName: $.lastName, Email: $.email, AccountId: vars.accountId }]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:create>
```

### Upsert (insert-or-update by external Id)

**CRITICAL (XSD / `mvn package`):** `<salesforce:upsert>` is **not** the same as create/update. The Salesforce connector schema requires **`objectType`** for the SObject name on upsert. Using **`type`** here fails Maven `process-classes` with:

- `Attribute 'type' is not allowed to appear in element 'salesforce:upsert'`
- `Attribute 'objectType' must appear on element 'salesforce:upsert'`

Keep using **`type`** on `<salesforce:create>`, `<salesforce:update>`, bulk ops, etc. Only upsert uses **`objectType`**.

```xml
<salesforce:upsert config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config"
             objectType="Account"
             externalIdFieldName="External_Id__c"
             doc:name="Upsert Account">
  <salesforce:records>#[[{ External_Id__c: payload.externalId, Name: payload.name }]]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:upsert>
```

### Update — by Salesforce Id
```xml
<salesforce:update config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Update Account">
  <salesforce:records>#[[{ Id: vars.accountId, Industry: payload.industry }]]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:update>
```

### Delete
```xml
<salesforce:delete config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" doc:name="Delete Account">
  <salesforce:ids>#[[vars.accountId]]</salesforce:ids>
</salesforce:delete>
```

### Query (SOQL)
```xml
<salesforce:query config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" doc:name="Query top accounts">
  <salesforce:salesforce-query>SELECT Id, Name, Industry FROM Account WHERE Industry = ':industry' LIMIT 50</salesforce:salesforce-query>
  <salesforce:parameters>#[{ industry: vars.industry }]</salesforce:parameters>
</salesforce:query>
```

### Query — `IN` with a **list** of values (dynamic keys)

**Do not** pass a Java/Array `List` to a single bound parameter (e.g. `WHERE MyField IN :keys` and `#[{ keys: vars.someArray }]`) unless you have confirmed your connector version maps it correctly. Many deployments throw:

`Unable to convert 'Array' to class 'java.lang.String'` (or similar) when the driver expects a **String** (or a different bind shape) for that placeholder.

**Preferred pattern** — build the `IN` clause in DataWeave with **single-quoted**, **comma-separated** literals and escape embedded apostrophes per SOQL (`'` → `''`):

```dw
fun escapeSoqlQuotes(s) = (s as String splitBy "'") joinBy "''"
var keys = vars.categoryKeys default []
var obj = vars.sfCategoryObjectType default ""
var inList = (keys map ((k) -> "'" ++ escapeSoqlQuotes(k) ++ "'")) joinBy ", "
---
"SELECT Id, Import_Key__c FROM " ++ obj ++ " WHERE Import_Key__c IN (" ++ inList ++ ")"
```

(`dw::core::Strings` **`replace`** is not a 3-argument substring replace in all DW versions — use **`splitBy "'" joinBy "''"`** for SOQL single-quote escaping.)

Use that string as the **only** `<salesforce:salesforce-query>` body — **no** `<salesforce:parameters>` for `keys`. Treat keys as untrusted unless they come from a strictly validated vocabulary (still escape `'`).

### Batching vs per-row DML and queries (`foreach`)

**Purpose:** Reduce **API calls**, runtime, and load on Salesforce **per-record** automation (triggers, flows). This is a **design guideline** — not a hard ban on `<foreach>`.

**Prefer (especially when row count N is large or the job runs frequently):**

- Build a **list** of SObject maps, then **one** (or **chunked**) `<salesforce:upsert>` / `create` / `update` with **many** rows in `<salesforce:records>` instead of **one connector DML per iteration**. Chunk (e.g. 200 rows) if you hit connector or platform limits.
- **Batch SOQL:** e.g. `WHERE Import_Key__c IN ('a','b',…)` for **distinct** keys from the batch — **not** a separate `query` per row. Chunk `IN` clauses to stay within **SOQL length** and **query row** limits.
- **In-memory join (DataWeave):** merge batched query results with the working payload (e.g. category Id by key, existing junction Ids) **before** issuing **batched** junction `create` / `update`.
- **Very large** volumes: prefer **Bulk API** operations (see Bulk Insert above) where appropriate.

**Per-row `<foreach>` that contains `salesforce:query` / `create` / `update` / `upsert` is acceptable when:**

- **N is small** (roughly **tens**; above **~50–200** re-evaluate; above **~500** strongly prefer batching), **or**
- **Business rules** require a **separate transaction** per record, **or**
- **Low-frequency** or **prototype** flows where simplicity is explicitly traded for API cost — document in **`JOBS.md`** (scheduled jobs) and/or **`PROJECT_CONTEXT.md`** §10.

**Scheduled syncs:** See **`mule-scheduler-jobs.mdc`** — agents should **not** treat "loop + DML every row" as the default finished design for **high-volume** file/DB loads without noting cost and **preferring** batching, **delta/watermark**, or **Bulk API**.

### Mandatory: chunk standard `upsert` / `create` / `update` lists at the SOAP 200-record ceiling

Salesforce documents the SOAP **`upsert()`** **`sObjects`** argument as an array with a **maximum of 200** records per call ([`upsert()` — Arguments](https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.api.meta/api/sforce_api_calls_upsert.htm)). The same **200** ceiling applies to other synchronous composite/collection DML patterns your connector may use under the hood.

The Mule **`Upsert`** operation reference describes a **list** of records; it does **not** promise to split oversized lists into multiple API calls for you ([Salesforce Connector — Upsert](https://docs.mulesoft.com/connectors/salesforce/salesforce-connector-reference#upsert)).

**Agents MUST** when a flow can send **more than 200** rows in one logical batch:

1. Add a **`config.yaml`** scalar (quoted string) for chunk size — e.g. `job.<jobName>.salesforceBatchSize: "200"` — and read it in DataWeave via `p("job.<jobName>.salesforceBatchSize")` (fallback **200**; if parsed size is below **1**, clamp to **200**).
2. Split the SObject list in DataWeave into **ordered** sub-arrays of **at most** that size (recursive slice pattern, e.g. `toBatches`).
3. Use **`<foreach collection="…">`** (one iteration **per chunk**, not per row) around `<salesforce:upsert>` / `create` / `update`, with **`salesforce:records` bound to the chunk** (`#[payload]` inside the scope).
4. **Merge** `(payload.items default [])` from each connector response **in order** into a single array (e.g. `vars.accumulated…Items`) **before** zipping with the original source rows or computing global success/failure counts.
5. Log batch count + merged record count at **INFO**; update **`JOBS.md`** / **`PROJECT_CONTEXT.md`** when changing scheduled jobs.

**Do not** rely on undocumented connector auto-chunking. For **very large** loads (tens of thousands+), prefer **Bulk API** job operations and document trade-offs in **`JOBS.md`**.

**Chunked `<foreach>`** (≤200 rows per iteration) is the standard compromise: it respects the platform limit while keeping **O(N/200)** connector calls instead of **N** per-row calls.

### Bulk Insert (10K+ records)
```xml
<salesforce:create-bulk config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Contact" doc:name="Bulk insert Contacts">
  <salesforce:records>#[payload]</salesforce:records>
</salesforce:create-bulk>
```
Use Bulk for > ~2000 records. Returns a `jobId` you can poll with `<salesforce:get-job-info>` and `<salesforce:get-batch-result>`.

## 5. The ACTUAL response shape from `salesforce:create` / `salesforce:update` / `salesforce:upsert`

The Mule SF connector returns a **BatchOperationResult** — NOT a flat `SaveResult` array. This is the most common cause of "my success check doesn't fire" or "I get 'no errors[]' even though SF rejected the record". Verified shape:

```json
{
  "successful": true,                      // overall batch success
  "id": null,                              // overall id (usually null for batches)
  "items": [                               // one entry per submitted record
    {
      "successful": true,                  // per-record success
      "id": "001fj00001AjjqjAAB",          // SF Id when created
      "exception": null,                   // populated only on connector/SOAP fault
      "message": null,                     // top-level error msg if any
      "statusCode": null,                  // top-level status if any
      "payload": {                         // the actual SaveResult from SF
        "success": true,
        "id": "001fj00001AjjqjAAB",
        "errors": [                        // populated on SF business rejection
          { "statusCode": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: ...", "fields": ["BillingCountry"] }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Always read `payload.items[N]` — never `payload[N]` — for SF results.** A single-record create still returns `items: [...]` with one entry.

## 6. MUST Rules

- **One global config per org** (Sandbox vs Prod), reused across all flows.
- **Set the SObject on each operation:** use **`type`** on `<salesforce:create>`, `<salesforce:update>`, `<salesforce:delete>`, bulk operations, etc. Use **`objectType`** on `<salesforce:upsert>` only (see §4 Upsert — XSD requires this name).
- **The `<salesforce:records>` payload MUST be a list `[{...}]`**, even for a single record. Wrap with `[ ... ]`.
- **Read results from `payload.items[N]`**, NOT `payload[N]`. See response shape above.
- **Treat `items[N].successful != true`** as a failure. Pull `items[N].payload.errors[0].statusCode` + `.message` + `.fields` for diagnostics.
- **NEVER hard-code credentials** in XML. Use `${...}` properties bound to env vars or secure-properties.
- **Test the connection** in ACB: open `global-configs.xml` → click the Salesforce config → "Test Connection".
- **Lists over ~200 rows:** chunk synchronous `upsert` / `create` / `update` per §4 *Mandatory: chunk standard DML…*; merge `payload.items` in source order before zipping with inputs.
- **Prefer batching over per-row DML** in `<foreach>` for non-trivial N — see §4 *Batching vs per-row DML and queries (`foreach`)*.

## 7. User-Friendly Error Responses — MANDATORY pattern

Every flow that calls Salesforce MUST surface SF errors in a clean, actionable JSON shape — never dump raw connector payloads to API consumers. The agent MUST follow this exact pattern:

### Step 1 — In the SUB-FLOW, capture two variables before raising

```xml
<ee:transform doc:name="Capture Salesforce error">
  <ee:variables>
    <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorCode"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item  = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs  = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
---
(first.statusCode default item.statusCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED") as String]]></ee:set-variable>
    <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorMessage"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item   = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs   = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first  = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
var fields = first.fields default []
var msg    = first.message default item.message default item.exception.detailMessage default "Salesforce rejected the request"
---
(if (sizeOf(fields) > 0) (msg ++ " (fields: " ++ (fields joinBy ", ") ++ ")") else msg) as String]]></ee:set-variable>
  </ee:variables>
</ee:transform>
<logger level="WARN" message="#['SFDC FAILED: ' ++ vars.sfErrorCode ++ ' - ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
<raise-error type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" description="#[vars.sfErrorCode ++ ': ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
```

### Step 2 — In the OUTER error handler, map SF statusCode to HTTP status

```xml
<on-error-propagate type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" doc:name="Salesforce rejected">
  <ee:transform doc:name="Map SF statusCode to HTTP">
    <ee:variables>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#[vars.sfErrorCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED"]</ee:set-variable>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[vars.sfErrorMessage default error.description]</ee:set-variable>
      <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var c = vars.sfErrorCode default ""
---
(if (c == "INVALID_FIELD" or c == "REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING" or c == "STRING_TOO_LONG" or c == "INVALID_DATE_FORMAT" or c == "INVALID_TYPE_ON_FIELD_IN_RECORD" or c == "MALFORMED_ID") 400
 else if (c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE" or c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE_DETECTED") 409
 else if (c == "REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED" or c == "STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED") 429
 else if (c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY" or c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_ON_CROSS_REFERENCE_ENTITY") 403
 else 422) as Number]]></ee:set-variable>
    </ee:variables>
  </ee:transform>
</on-error-propagate>
```

### Result — what the API consumer sees

```json
// 400 — caller's input is malformed
{ "code": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: invalid country code 'XYZ' (fields: BillingCountry)" }

// 409 — uniqueness violated
{ "code": "DUPLICATE_VALUE", "message": "duplicate value found: ExternalId__c (fields: ExternalId__c)" }

// 422 — generic SF business rejection
{ "code": "FIELD_CUSTOM_VALIDATION_EXCEPTION", "message": "Account name must start with capital letter" }

// 503 — SF unreachable (handled by SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY handler, separate)
{ "code": "SALESFORCE_UNAVAILABLE", "message": "Connection refused" }
```

NEVER return:
- Raw connector payloads (no `items: [...]` in API responses)
- Generic strings like "Salesforce rejected the request" — always include the `statusCode` and the actual `message`
- Stack traces or `error.description` directly without unwrapping it through this pattern

## 8. SF statusCode → HTTP status mapping (canonical)

| SF statusCode | HTTP | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `INVALID_FIELD` | 400 | Caller sent an unknown/invalid field value |
| `REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING` | 400 | Required field not provided |
| `STRING_TOO_LONG` | 400 | Value exceeds field max length |
| `INVALID_DATE_FORMAT` | 400 | Date couldn't be parsed |
| `MALFORMED_ID` | 400 | SF Id format invalid |
| `DUPLICATE_VALUE` / `_DETECTED` | 409 | Unique constraint hit |
| `REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED` | 429 | Org API limit |
| `STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED` | 429 | Org storage limit |
| `INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY` | 403 | User lacks permission |
| `FIELD_CUSTOM_VALIDATION_EXCEPTION` | 422 | A validation rule fired |
| `INVALID_FIELD_FOR_INSERT_UPDATE` | 422 | Field exists but not writable here |
| anything else | 422 | Generic SF business rejection |

## 9. Inserting Salesforce Records — Reference Flow (uses the patterns above)

Validate input → transform to SF object → create → check `items[0].successful` → return id, OR capture SF error and raise with the user-friendly pattern from §7.

```xml
<flow name="accounts-create-flow">
  <http:listener config-ref="HTTP_Listener_config" path="/api/v1/accounts" allowedMethods="POST" doc:name="POST /accounts">
    <http:response statusCode="201"/>
    <http:error-response statusCode="#[vars.httpStatus default 500]">
      <http:body>#[output application/json --- { code: vars.errorCode, message: vars.errorMessage }]</http:body>
    </http:error-response>
  </http:listener>

  <ee:transform doc:name="Map to SF Account">
    <ee:message>
      <ee:set-payload><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
---
[{
  Name: payload.name default "",
  Industry: payload.industry default "Other",
  BillingCity: payload.city
}]
]]></ee:set-payload>
    </ee:message>
  </ee:transform>

  <salesforce:create config-ref="Salesforce_Sandbox_config" type="Account" doc:name="Create Account"/>

  <choice doc:name="Check SF result">
    <when expression="#[((payload.items default [])[0].successful default false) == true]">
      <ee:transform doc:name="Build 201 response">
        <ee:message>
          <ee:set-payload><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/json
var item = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
---
{ id: item.id default item.payload.id default "(no-id)", status: "created" }
]]></ee:set-payload>
        </ee:message>
      </ee:transform>
    </when>
    <otherwise>
      <!-- Capture using the §7 pattern -->
      <ee:transform doc:name="Capture SF error">
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorCode"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item  = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs  = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
---
(first.statusCode default item.statusCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED") as String]]></ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="sfErrorMessage"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var item   = (payload.items default [])[0] default {}
var errs   = (item.payload.errors default [])
var first  = if (sizeOf(errs) > 0) errs[0] else {}
var fields = first.fields default []
var msg    = first.message default item.message default item.exception.detailMessage default "Salesforce rejected the request"
---
(if (sizeOf(fields) > 0) (msg ++ " (fields: " ++ (fields joinBy ", ") ++ ")") else msg) as String]]></ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
      <raise-error type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR" description="#[vars.sfErrorCode ++ ': ' ++ vars.sfErrorMessage]"/>
    </otherwise>
  </choice>

  <error-handler>
    <on-error-propagate type="SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY">
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">503</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#["SALESFORCE_UNAVAILABLE"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[error.description]</ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
    <on-error-propagate type="APP:SALESFORCE_ERROR">
      <!-- Uses the §7 mapping (vars.sfErrorCode → HTTP) -->
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#[vars.sfErrorCode default "SALESFORCE_REJECTED"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[vars.sfErrorMessage default error.description]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
var c = vars.sfErrorCode default ""
---
(if (c == "INVALID_FIELD" or c == "REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING" or c == "STRING_TOO_LONG" or c == "MALFORMED_ID") 400
 else if (c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE" or c == "DUPLICATE_VALUE_DETECTED") 409
 else if (c == "REQUEST_LIMIT_EXCEEDED" or c == "STORAGE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED") 429
 else if (c == "INSUFFICIENT_ACCESS_OR_READONLY") 403
 else 422) as Number]]></ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
    <on-error-propagate type="ANY">
      <ee:transform>
        <ee:variables>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">500</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">#["INTERNAL_ERROR"]</ee:set-variable>
          <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">#[error.description default "Unexpected error"]</ee:set-variable>
        </ee:variables>
      </ee:transform>
    </on-error-propagate>
  </error-handler>
</flow>
```

## 10. Common Errors

| Error type | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `SALESFORCE:INVALID_SESSION_ID` | Token expired | Connector auto-refreshes; if persists, check creds |
| `SALESFORCE:CONNECTIVITY` | Network / org down / wrong url | Verify Sandbox vs Prod URL |
| `INVALID_FIELD` in `errors[]` | Field name typo or invalid value | Check SObject in Salesforce Setup; surface via §7 pattern |
| `REQUIRED_FIELD_MISSING` | A required SObject field wasn't supplied | Add it in the DataWeave mapping |
| `DUPLICATE_VALUE` | Hit a unique constraint | Use `upsert` instead of `create` |
| Mule reports success but caller sees `SALESFORCE_REJECTED` | Reading `payload[0]` instead of `payload.items[0]` | Apply §6 + §7 patterns |

## 11. Local Testing

Mock the Salesforce connector in MUnit (see `mule-testing-munit.mdc`). For end-to-end, point the global config at a **Salesforce Developer Sandbox** — never test against Production.

```powershell
$body = @{ name = "Acme Inc"; industry = "Technology"; city = "London" } | ConvertTo-Json
Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8081/api/v1/accounts" `
  -Method POST -Body $body -ContentType "application/json"
```
